snippet.textDisplay:
I remember my dad having cancer since I was 6. We lived in a state with not the medical supplies to support my father so we had to travel to a different state. It was so sudden. In a single day, my dad, mom and me were rushed on an airplane, leaving my sister behind with family. I missed 4 months of school, staying in hospital to hospital. I enrolled in a school. I remember that day vividly. I crossed the road with a random adult and went up the steps of my aunts house. I knocked on the door, twice, three times, four times. No answer. A boy about 11-12 look at me with a frown like he knew something bad was going to happen. I slammed my little hand on the door when my uncle opened the door. I ran upstairs to see my mom crying. I asked her what happened and she said "daddy past away." I cried harder than any i have ever. The next day, I told my teacher. My first grade teacher. All I remember her saying is "I'm sorry honey." And called me out to the hallway. She handed me a teddy bear with a heart and said "here take this." Then everything went to a blur.

It happens at some point in our lives. It's a sadness we all can't explain. My condolences and blessing to everyone as the people who have had a family member (s) that have passed away from cancer.
there I go again, crying.

snippet.textDisplay: I was finally able to sit down at watch this documentary and I’m so glad that I did. I found myself sobbing through the entire thing because mine is so extremely similar. Hearing the way people talked about Sean and how amazing he is reminded me of my grandpa. They were so similar and my story is oddly, in a way, the same as there’s. My grandfather was diagnosed with stage 4 stomach cancer in September of 2016. He too passed away after a 2 and a half year long battle on January 19, 2019. It was the hardest day of my entire life. He was my best friend. This has been the hardest year of my life, and I’m so glad that I was able to watch this documentary and know that everything that I’ve been feeling normal. I feel that after watching this documentary it has made me realize that I’m not alone, and I shouldn’t be afraid to talk about it and let my emotions show. Fly high Papa and Sean, and may your wonderful souls never be forgotten. ❤️ Thank you Ethan and Grayson for sharing your story with the rest of us. ❤️❤️

snippet.textDisplay: this was really touching. about a year ago, my uncle passed away suddenly, from cardiac arrest. he was only in his 50s and his 2 sons (my cousins) were 16 and 18. my aunt didn't know how to drive and she was also losing her vision. her 2 sons suddenly had a lot on their shoulders, as the "man" of the family. paperwork to fill out, a mom to take care of, and coming of age on top of the sudden loss of their best friend. a man with a really unique sense of humor who was able to make light of anything, no matter how serious. seeing this video about you 2, brothers, made me think of my cousins and their journey through a similar battle. i remember thinking about how i never saw the younger one shed one tear or express any emotion, even when holding his father's hand in the viewing. but i also saw how he felt like he needed to be strong for his mom, how he needed to step up and take care of business. later on he even expressed how he didn't want to have a gf because he didn't want to leave his mom at home alone for too long, because she would get sad. there is so much pressure on how to act after losing a loved one like your father, at a young age. very selfless of you guys to think that you had to be a certain kind of person to make your dad proud , or to grieve correctly without judgment. i am sure his spirit is within you, and in that way, he will live on. glad you made this documentary to encapsulate his life and honor his memory.

snippet.textDisplay: How many people can actually say they made such a big impact on others? It sucks how these sicknesses take away so many loved ones. My grand-mother battled with cancer for more than a decade on and of, she past at the age of 52. She was one of the most generous people you could imagine. When my mom a couple years ago got diagnosed with cancer herself everyone around broke (especially my grand-father and uncle, having been on the first line watching my grand-mother go through the same thing. I will never forget my cousin calling me after witnessing her father cry for the first time in her life. My father didn't show anything, trying to be strong for my mom, but I knew...). She stayed strong, she too didn't show how badly it affected her. I learned only a few month ago that she actually got diagnosed, at the time with a stage 4 breast cancer. You wouldn't have guessed talking to her. She got through it. But she got through so much bullshit through her entire life. Always doing every thing she can for others. Even now, she changed vocation to become a psychoanalyst to help people affected by cancer and their families with the process, and the aftermath. So many people diagnosed with cancer don't have the money to get the proper treatments, what you are doing is amazing, these things aren't talked about enough, especially what the people around them go through. People see the sickness and forget the actual people going through them. Ok I'm going to stop here otherwise I'll keep writing for hours. Even though I am lucky enough not to know what the death of someone so important feels like, I know how it is feeling powerless, doing everything you can to help but not being able to do anything. All my love to everyone...

snippet.textDisplay: I just lost my mom to brain cancer in August of 2019. snippet.textDisplay: Such an incredible heartfelt raw story. You guys have used your platform to share your creativity and your love for your father in such a beautiful touching way. You guys are so admirable and smart and motivational. I own a hair replacement business in the Bay Area, ca. For those wondering what that means I cater specifically to cancer patients who are losing their hair due to chemotherapy and any other disease than affects ones hair. I'm a small business owner but have been doing this for over 15years. The oncology departments in these cancer centers are in awe of my work and send all their patients my way. Seeing the shave down when you were parting ways with your hair is a very real thing. I too offer that service to all my patients and it's a very emotional experience to have to go through because it's a lot of peoples identity. Hair is a big part of our image and it's our comfort and to have  it taken away from you is a Loss of control for some people. But liberating because people are ready to fight the fight. Thanks for enlightening those who aren't educated about loss and cancer you guys are beautiful souls and you'll always have each other. God bless!!!
snippet.textOriginal: Such an incredible heartfelt raw story. You guys have used your platform to share your creativity and your love for your father in such a beautiful touching way. You guys are so admirable and smart and motivational. I own a hair replacement business in the Bay Area, ca. For those wondering what that means I cater specifically to cancer patients who are losing their hair due to chemotherapy and any other disease than affects ones hair. I'm a small business owner but have been doing this for over 15years. The oncology departments in these cancer centers are in awe of my work and send all their patients my way. Seeing the shave down when you were parting ways with your hair is a very real thing. I too offer that service to all my patients and it's a very emotional experience to have to go through because it's a lot of peoples identity.
